                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Just to sum it up:
<br />

<br />
  So i charmed some level 67 dragorn mob in Ruined City today with Compel, expecting it would hit for within at least 300-380 range, but it was hitting for exactly 260. We had level 67 rogue in group, and he said that mob was white to him, so i'm more or less certain it was in fact 67. When this pet broke, it proceed to quad me for full 731 damage per swing. Now that i'm well time/GoD geared, and have just over 8k hp buffed, but even then no way in hell i would do this again without Divine Intervention being cast by a cleric. Saved me twice within 30 minutes.
<br />
I then proceed, and charmed level 66 elite kyv lala something. Blue /con to lvl 67 rogue, but Sleep (cap 65) wont land, so its certainly level 66. Hits for mid-600's when not charmed. Same 260 as the above dragorn when charmed.
<br />

<br />
For example mobs, that can be charmed by CoD (lvl 64 cap), always hit for 245 in Ruined City. Hit for low 600's when not charmed.
<br />

<br />
In conclusion, i doubt there is any special code, that limits every single mob based by what its uncharmed damage is, and adds variety. I think their damage is manually cut based by zone or maybe even mob model. Level 65+ stuff in WoS hits for 260 too when charmed.
<br />

<br />
I now know for sure there was an one-minute thought out, bandaid, incomplete and incompetent solution with "charm is way too powerful" problem. Same as our OoW spells were mindlessly copied from our PoP ones. Second statement is true for nearly every other class though.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
