                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">For crying out loud, if you're using charm for crowd control you don't use it when they're incoming unless you're using a dictate-like spell with their -1000 MR adjustment, you use it when you have to many mezzed mobs in camp to help speed up mob removal and expand the number of mobs you can keep under control.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
One question do you play an enchanter?  If you are in the rare situation where you are holding down a large number of hard hitting mobs, you do not go and charm one of them.  As it is you are to busy tashing and slowing and keeping all the mobs mez, to have any extra time  to watch a charmed pet.  The last thing you want to do is take a situation where everything is undercontrol and add some risk by charming a mob that puts out substandard DPS.  Now if you are in a gimp zone where the enchanter can tank 2 of the slowed mobs easy, then go ahead and have some fun and charm one of the mobs.
<br />

<br />
And yes before COD was nerfed the first time, it was the perfect spell to help CC with, by charming a mob on inc.  Back then COD was hard to resist and lasted most times long enough for us to get the other mobs all mez.  Plus our pets back then did a good job holding aggro, allowing you to tash and mez a mob without getting aggro if the pet was tanking it.
<br />

<br />
A dictate charm does not last long enough for us to bother keeping it mem at all times and use it as a form of CC.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Not everything crowd control related has to be done when  the mobs are coming into camp.  Do you slow and tash every single incoming mob before mezzing it</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
When you have multiply inc mobs you do not have time to play around, the situation needs to get undercontrol very fast or else the group is dead.  Anything you do has to work fast, you do not have time to mez a mob, tash it, charm it and then wait for mez to wear off before you mez the other mobs.  Your cleric will be long dead if you waste time tashing and then charming a mez mob, while allowing other mobs to run around killing everyone.  And like I said above once all mobs are mez, you do not add more risk by adding a substandard dps pet to the situation.  If charm does not work on inc. and does not last over 2 minutes on average it is not going to be worth using as a CC tool.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
